Abstract

Aim

   To assess the effectiveness of protected areas in preventing
   biodiversity decline. We first test whether species richness of
   butterfly assemblages is higher within European Natura 2000 (N2000)
   sites than in their surroundings. We then assess temporal trends in
   butterfly richness and test whether these trends differ inside and
   outside the N2000 network.

Location

   Germany, Europe.

Methods

   We utilized generalized linear mixed‐effects models (GLMM) to analyse
   an 11‐year data series on species richness of butterfly assemblages
   collected on 245 transects across Germany, located inside and outside
   N2000 sites, and comprising a total of 122 butterfly species.

Results

   Butterfly species richness was highest inside N2000 protected areas,
   while outside it constantly declined with increasing distance from
   N2000 sites. We found an overall decline in species richness by 10%
   within 11 years. This decline neither differed between transects
   located inside or outside the N2000 network nor varied with distance
   from N2000 sites.

Main conclusions

   The higher species richness inside the N2000 network underlines their
   proper designation and their potential for the conservation of
   biodiversity. However, the current negative trend in butterfly species
   richness across Germany is not mitigated by the N2000 network, and we
   assume insufficient management or measures targeted at other organisms
   than butterflies as potential reasons.

1 INTRODUCTION

   In spite of nationally and internationally set goals and introduced
   policies, we are currently experiencing an undiminished decline of
   biodiversity (Brooks et al., 2012; Butchart et al., 2010; Eskildsen
   et al., 2015; Tittensor et al., 2014). In Europe, the cornerstone of
   species protection policy is the Natura 2000 (N2000) network of
   protected areas (EC, 2010). The N2000 network is one of the most
   important and largest conservation networks of the world (Hochkirch
   et al., 2013; Lockwood, 2006), currently covering over 18% of the EU′s
   land surface (EC, 2015a). It has been based on two basic directives—the
   “Birds Directive” targeted on the conservation of birds (EEC, 1979) and
   the “Habitats Directive” focussing on selected threatened species and
   habitats (EEC, 1992).

   Several studies already investigated the effectiveness of designation,
   that is, how well the N2000 network covers the distribution of
   threatened species or the diversity of certain taxonomic groups (e.g.,
   D'Amen et al., 2013; Guareschi, Bilton, Velasco, Millán, & Abellán,
   2015; Maiorano et al., 2015; Trochet & Schmeller, 2013; Van der Sluis
   et al., 2016; Verovnik, Govedič, & Šalamun, 2011). These studies
   conclude that, with a few exceptions, the coverage of biodiversity is
   largely satisfactory.

   In addition to the successful designation of areas of high
   biodiversity, an even more critical measure of success would be the
   ability of protected areas to diminish, halt or even reverse the
   currently observed negative trends in biodiversity. Published trends of
   target and non‐target species (usually mammals and birds) in protected
   areas across the world tend to be rather positive (Barnes et al., 2016;
   Geldmann et al., 2013; Laurance et al., 2012), but have rarely been
   compared with populations outside protected areas.

   Studies assessing trends in species richness or abundance to evaluate
   the efficiency of the European N2000 network over time are scarce, and
   all of them focus on birds. These studies found predominantly positive
   trends of species protected under the Birds Directive, in particular
   flagship and specialized species, which seems to indicate an overall
   success of EU legislation (Donald et al., 2007; Sanderson et al.,
   2016), while for common and non‐target species, the pattern appears to
   be ambiguous (Devictor, Godet, Julliard, Couvet, & Jiguet, 2007;
   Pellissier, Touroult, Julliard, Siblet, & Jiguet, 2013; Santana et al.,
   2014). Given the low number of studies and their limitation to a few
   taxonomic groups, a general assessment of the extent to which the N2000
   network can reduce negative trends is currently hardly possible.

   Here, we assess the effectiveness of N2000 sites in preventing the
   decline of biodiversity using butterflies as an example for a
   non‐target species group. Butterflies are a popular group of insects
   which is appreciated by the public for their aesthetic, symbolic and
   intrinsic value (Potts et al., 2016). Moreover, as primary consumers,
   pollinators and prey they fulfil important roles in ecosystem
   functioning and are often used as indicators for the assessment of the
   state of ecosystems (Erhardt & Thomas, 1991; Van Swaay, Warren, & Loïs,
   2006; Zografou, Sfenthourakis, Pullin, & Kati, 2009). They are
   frequently an object of research and probably the most surveyed group
   of insects, at least in Europe (Van Swaay, Nowicki, Settele, & Van
   Strien, 2008; Van Swaay et al., 2006). These qualities predestine
   butterflies to be a convenient surrogate for less conspicuous taxa
   (Thomas et al., 2004). Butterflies can act as flagship and umbrella
   species and thus contribute to the conservation of habitats and other
   organisms (Maes & Van Dyck, 2005; Simberloff, 1998; Spitzer, Beneš,
   Dandová, Jašková, & Konvička, 2009). In our study, we used time series
   data on species richness of butterflies across Germany to address two
   particular aims: (a) To test whether butterfly species richness is
   higher in N2000 areas compared to their surroundings and (b) to assess
   overall temporal trends in species richness of butterfly assemblages
   and whether these trends differ inside and outside the N2000 network.

2 METHODS

2.1 Study sites and butterfly data

   We used data from the German Butterfly Monitoring Scheme
   (www.tagfalter-monitoring.de). Here, monitoring has been conducted by
   volunteers since 2005 according to a standardized protocol (see Kühn
   et al., 2008 for details). Data quality is checked by experts, and the
   data are centrally managed. The number of transects has been growing
   over time; therefore, there are 11‐year data series for the oldest
   transects and shorter series for the others, covering 5–11 years.
   Transect data at different time spans (i.e., number of years of
   observation) were evenly distributed, resulting in about 40 transect
   data per time span. Transects also differed in length, but each
   transect consists of several sections with a standard length of 50 m.
   For our analysis, we selected transects with 5–20 sections, resulting
   in 245 transects distributed all across Germany (Supporting Information
   Figure S1). We excluded data points with less than two species per year
   and transect leading to 1993 transect‐year combinations for our
   analysis.

   We used a map of N2000 sites obtained from the European Environmental
   Agency (EEA, 2011) to identify the position of the transects with the
   GIS software SAGA 2.1.4 in two ways. Transects overlaying at least
   partly with N2000 sites were considered as “inside.” About 28% of the
   considered transects were inside N2000 areas, which is larger than the
   overall coverage of N2000 areas in Germany (15.5%; EC, 2015a). We also
   measured the distance of individual transects (centre points) from the
   boundary of the closest N2000 site using the function near, implemented
   in the software ArcGis 10.2.

   We included occurrence data of 122 species of true butterflies
   (families Nymphalidae, Pieridae, Lycaenidae, Riodinidae, Papilionidae)
   and skippers (family Hesperiidae). Hardly distinguishable species were
   treated as complexes resulting in a final list of 115 items (Supporting
   Information Table S1).

   To account for potential differences in habitat suitability among
   transects within and outside N2000 areas, we computed a “habitat
   suitability index” (hsi) for each transect, which basically weights the
   amount of a particular habitat type by the number of species that are
   associated with this habitat type. In particular, we used habitat data
   from the Map of European ecosystem types (European Environment Agency,
   http://biodiversity.europa.eu/maes) classified according to EUNIS
   habitat classification level 2 (EEA, 2014) and calculated the
   percentage of each habitat type within a 1 km radius around each
   transect centre point. To assess habitat associations, we extracted the
   number of butterfly species associated with each habitat type from
   Reinhardt, Sbieschne, Settele, Fischer, and Fiedler (2007). Finally,
   the percentage of a habitat type occurring within the buffer zone of a
   particular transect was multiplied by the number of its associated
   butterfly species and the hsi was calculated as the sum of all habitat
   specific values in the buffer zone.

2.2 Data analysis

   All statistical analyses were performed using the software r 3.3.2 (R
   Core Team, 2016). We computed species richness (as number of species)
   for each sampling year within each transect. To test for the effect of
   N2000 sites on species richness of butterfly assemblages, their overall
   temporal trends and hypothesized differences in trends between N2000
   sites and their surroundings, we constructed generalized linear
   mixed‐effects models (GLMM) with a Poisson distribution and log link
   function, using the R package lme4 version 1.1‐12 (Bates, Maechler,
   Bolker, & Walker, 2014). We used the location of transects (inside or
   outside) or, alternatively, the distance of transects from the nearest
   N2000 area to test for differences in species richness within and
   outside N2000 areas. We included year (scaled to mean zero and unit
   standard deviation) as a further explanatory variable to assess overall
   temporal trends in species richness and the interaction of year and
   location (inside or outside) or distance to test for differences in
   trends. The relevance of this interaction was assessed according to
   resulting p‐values. We also included transect length as a covariable to
   account for potential sampling effects. To account for potential
   problems of pseudoreplication, we included transect as a random effect
   allowing for random intercepts and random slopes of year. To control
   for potentially confounding effects of general differences in overall
   habitat suitability inside and outside N2000 areas, we alternatively
   computed models including hsi (scaled to mean zero and unit standard
   deviation) as an additional variable which lead to four models in total
   (Supporting Information Table S2). All models were checked for spatial
   autocorrelation in the residuals by computing overall Moran's I using
   the R package ncf version 1.1‐7 (Bjornstad, 2013), but no spatial
   autocorrelation was found. We used the R package effects version 4.0‐0
   (Fox, 2003) for visualizing the results.

3 RESULTS

   According to our expectations, butterfly species richness was higher
   within N2000 sites than outside (Figure 1a; Supporting Information
   Table S2) and it constantly decreased with growing distance from the
   N2000 sites (Figure 1b, Supporting Information Table S2). Models using
   location (inside or outside N2000) or distance were both statistically
   significant, but according to AIC values, the distance from N2000
   appeared to be a better predictor of butterfly diversity than the
   location (delta AIC > 2; Supporting Information Table S2). The effect
   of distance may be attributed to habitat availability in the
   surroundings of N2000 sites. However, the effect of hsi on species
   richness was not statistically significant (p = 0.11 and 0.13,
   respectively), while the effect of location and distance remained
   significant (models M3 and M4 in Supporting Information Table S2). The
   hsi in buffer zones around transects did not differ significantly
   within or outside N2000 areas (Welch two‐sample t test: t = 1.88,
   df = 100.1, p = 0.063) but decreased with growing distance from N2000
   sites (linear regression: coefficient = −0.57, SE = 0.29, t = 1.97,
   p = 0.050).
   image
   Figure 1
   Open in figure viewerPowerPoint
   Modelled butterfly species richness outside and inside N2000 sites (a)
   and as a function of distance from the closest N2000 site (b). Black
   bars and grey bands indicate 95% confidence intervals; ticks on the
   x‐axis in (b) are individual transects

   We also found that butterfly species richness declined over the
   11 years of observation (Figure 2, Supporting Information Table S2).
   The overall mean decline was 10%—from an average of 19.5 to 17.5
   species per transect. However, we did not find an interaction effect
   between N2000 sites and year (neither for location nor for distance) in
   any of the four models (M1: p = 0.35, M2: p = 0.93, M3: p = 0.47, M4:
   p = 0.91), indicating that the negative trends in species richness did
   not differ between N2000 sites and their surroundings (Figure 3).
   image
   Figure 2
   Open in figure viewerPowerPoint
   Modelled trend in species richness of butterfly assemblages across
   time. Grey bands indicate 95% confidence intervals
   image
   Figure 3
   Open in figure viewerPowerPoint
   Species richness trends of butterfly assemblages outside and inside
   N2000 sites. Grey bands indicate 95% confidence intervals

4 DISCUSSION

   We found that N2000 areas harboured more butterfly species than their
   surroundings as expected. This result suggests a proper designation of
   the N2000 network and that these sites are of overall high conservation
   importance. Several previous studies at the European scale on mammals
   and birds also showed that the majority of species (both target and
   non‐target) seems to be well covered by the current extent of the N2000
   network (Maiorano et al., 2015; Trochet & Schmeller, 2013; Van der
   Sluis et al., 2016), but see Albuquerque, Assunção‐Albuquerque,
   Cayuelac, Zamoraa, and Benitoa (2013). For insects and other
   invertebrates, only regional assessments have been performed and their
   results are equivocal (D'Amen et al., 2013; Guareschi et al., 2015;
   Hernandez‐Manrique, Numa, Verdu, Galante, & Lobo, 2012). The only
   detailed study on butterflies showed that hotspots of species richness
   in Slovenia are well covered by the N2000 network (Verovnik et al.,
   2011).

   We also found that the distance from N2000 sites is a better predictor
   of butterfly richness than a simpler inside–outside approach. We
   propose two not mutually exclusive explanations for this phenomenon.
   The first is related to a gradual decrease in the availability of
   suitable butterfly habitats with increasing distance from N2000 sites.
   N2000 sites often represent the most diverse or particularly important
   parts within an overall valuable landscape (e.g., Verovnik et al.,
   2011). In such landscapes, butterfly species are likely to thrive
   accordingly well also outside the protected areas. Indeed, the amount
   of suitable habitat tended to decrease with growing distance from
   protected areas, indicating that such gradual changes in landscape
   structure can at least partly explain the distance effect. However,
   even when the amount of suitable habitat was considered in the models,
   a pure distance effect remained. One reason might be that not only
   habitat availability decreased with distance from N2000 sites but also
   the quality, for example, in terms of resource availability or
   management intensity (Kleijn & Van Langevelde, 2006).

   A second likely explanation of the observed distance effect relates to
   source‐sink dynamics (Furrer & Pasinelli, 2016; Pulliam, 1988) in a
   metapopulation context (Hanski, 1998). According to this concept,
   species may persist under less favourable conditions outside the N2000
   areas, because they may constantly immigrate from N2000 sites where the
   environmental conditions allow high population growth rates (Furrer &
   Pasinelli, 2016; Hanski, 1998). The observed distance effect is then
   defined by the dispersal ability (Furrer & Pasinelli, 2016) of the
   species within a particular assemblage. Given such a potential source
   effect of N2000 sites, our results not only confirm the importance of
   N2000 sites for protecting biodiversity within the network but also
   highlight their beneficial effects in their surroundings. However, this
   cannot be an excuse for bad management outside the N2000 network, since
   in the same way as protected areas are positively influencing their
   surroundings, detrimental forces in the surroundings can also
   negatively influence protected areas (Laurance et al., 2012).

   Most worryingly, we found an overall decline in butterfly species
   richness at German monitoring sites of 10% between 2005 and 2015.
   Although our study covered only Germany, our results suggest that
   similar processes of local species extinctions may occur in other
   European regions. Indeed, Maes and Van Dyck (2001) showed a strong
   decrease in the number of butterfly species in northern Belgium during
   the 20th century. A similar pattern was found in Denmark, where the
   most severe declines occurred between 1960 and 1979 and moderate
   declines continued in subsequent periods such as between 2000 and 2012
   (Eskildsen et al., 2015). Local species extinctions are often preceded
   by a decline in population abundance or density, which corresponds well
   to the decreasing abundances in butterfly populations as it has been
   shown, for example, by the European grassland butterfly indicator (Van
   Swaay et al., 2008, 2015). Another recent study showed a more than 75%
   decline in flying insect biomass in German protected areas (Hallmann
   et al., 2017). Potential causes of such declines are habitat loss
   (Sang, Teder, Helm, & Pärtel, 2010), fragmentation (Hanski, 2015;
   Krauss et al., 2010), habitat degradation (Stefanescu, Peñuelas, &
   Filella, 2009) or climate change (Oliver et al., 2015; Schweiger,
   Settele, Kudrna, Klotz, & Kühn, 2008; Settele, Bishop, & Potts, 2016;
   Settele et al., 2008).

   Despite generally higher butterfly species richness within N2000
   protected areas, their designation has obviously not prevented a loss
   of species over time. This result leads to the question whether current
   management of N2000 areas is generally suited to prevent such losses.
   Many butterfly species in Europe depend on habitats that require active
   management (grazing, mowing, coppicing etc.; see Van Swaay et al.,
   2012) to preserve them in a favourable state. This is especially true
   for European grasslands (Rundlöf, Bengtsson, & Smith, 2008; Van Swaay
   et al., 2012, 2015), the major habitat type of European butterflies.
   According to the last assessment of the state of nature in the European
   Union, grasslands are generally in an unfavourable conservation status
   across Europe (EC, 2015b). This situation holds true also for Germany,
   although there was a slight improvement since the previous assessment
   (EC, 2014). In Germany, comprehensive management plans have been
   adopted for only 20% of the entire network area (EC, 2014). Such a lack
   of management can lead to degradation and overgrowing, particularly of
   grasslands, by highly competitive vegetation of later successional
   stages (Collins & Beaufoy, 2012; Lindenmayer et al., 2007; Spitzer
   et al., 2009) and thus potentially contribute to the observed declines
   in butterfly richness. However, even if management plans are
   implemented, they might be inadequate for butterflies, for example,
   when agricultural intensity is too high (Konvička et al., 2008) or when
   management is targeted towards other organisms (Lindenmayer et al.,
   2007), or the time span since implementation was too short for being
   effective (Woodcock et al., 2012).

   We conclude that there is a notable decline in species richness of
   butterflies across Germany but the N2000 protected areas do currently
   not qualify as an effective mitigation measure. We argue that one of
   the main causes is the absence or insufficient implementation of
   management. We believe that negative biodiversity trends could be
   mitigated by fully implementing the European Habitats Directive which
   has not been done so far (Maes et al., 2013). This includes
   improvements in management, the allocation of funds towards targeted
   biodiversity support and enhanced monitoring (Collins & Beaufoy, 2012;
   Hochkirch et al., 2013; Hodge, Hauck, & Bonn, 2015; Potts et al.,
   2016). Furthermore, future management concepts need to consider a wider
   biodiversity context and should also take into account the mitigation
   of other potential drivers such as climate change. With respect to
   butterflies (and many other organisms as well), this means, for
   example, a stronger consideration of the landscape context in
   conservation planning and management for heterogeneity of habitats
   across space and time (Dennis, 2010; Papanikolaou, Kühn, Frenzel, &
   Schweiger, 2017; Van Swaay et al., 2012).

ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS

   We thank volunteers from all over Germany who participated in German
   Butterfly Monitoring and collected data on butterflies in the field. We
   very appreciate comments and suggestions of Alan Andersen and an
   anonymous referee, which noticeably improved quality of the manuscript.
   This study was supported by the Scholarship Programme of the Deutsche
   Bundesstiftung Umwelt (AZ 30015/556) and by an internal grant from
   Palacký University IGA_PrF_2017_015 (both to SR).

