Abstract

   Gallbladder cancer is a common malignancy of the gastrointestinal tract
   that shows wide geographical variation in its distribution. Cause of
   gallbladder cancer is still obscure; however, various etiological
   factors have been proposed. Of these gallstones and inflammation of the
   gallbladder is commonest. Despite three decades of active research no
   conclusive evidence is available as to what causes gallbladder cancer?
   In this article we reviewed the evidence on the role of environmental
   pollutants on gallbladder carcinogenesis. A detailed search of Medline
   was carried out which revealed only 12 articles. A number of heavy
   metals like nickel, cadmium, etc. have been implicated; however, the
   evidence is not robust enough to conclude its association. Role of
   radiation and pesticides in river water have also been evaluated
   without any conclusive evidence of its association with gallbladder
   cancer. Better designed case‐control studies or cohort studies looking
   at exposure are required before it could be accepted as one of the
   causes of GBC. J. Surg. Oncol. 2006;93:640–643. © 2006 Wiley‐Liss, Inc.

